        <div class="section">
            <h2>Welcome to the Pilot</h2>
            <p class="welcome-text">
                You've been selected as one of 10 founding riders who will help shape Your Dressage Journey. Over the next 8 weeks, you'll transform how you track, understand, and accelerate your riding progress through systematic reflection and AI-powered pattern analysis.
            </p>
            <div class="emphasis">
                <strong>Your Role:</strong> You're not just a user‚Äîyou're a co-creator. Your feedback, frustrations, and suggestions will directly shape this platform. We're building this together, and your honest input matters more than anything else.
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Getting Started (First 15 Minutes)</h2>
            
            <ol class="numbered-steps">
                <li>
                    <strong>Bookmark the Post-Ride Debrief Form on Your Phone</strong>
                    This is your primary daily tool. Save it to your phone's home screen for instant access at the barn. You'll use this after every ride‚Äîthe memories are freshest right after you dismount.
                </li>

                <li>
                    <strong>Bookmark the Reflection Form on Your Phone</strong>
                    This is for deeper weekly reflections. Save it alongside the debrief form. We'll send you weekly reminders to complete a reflection, but don't wait for the reminder if you're inspired to capture something meaningful!
                </li>

                <li>
                    <strong>(Optional) Bookmark the Observation Form</strong>
                    For capturing insights from watching others‚Äîclinics, your trainer riding your horse, videos, or shows. This is completely optional but valuable when opportunities arise.
                </li>

                <li>
                    <strong>Test Voice Input</strong>
                    All forms support voice input on mobile. Practice using the microphone icon in a text field‚Äîthis is a game-changer for quick entries while untacking or capturing observations on the go.
                </li>
            </ol>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° Pro Tip: Mobile-First Setup</h4>
                <p>You'll do most of your data entry on your phone at the barn. Set yourself up for success by bookmarking all three forms and practicing voice input before your first post-pilot ride.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Your Daily Workflow</h2>
            
            <h3>After Every Ride (2-5 Minutes)</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 20px;">Open the <strong>Post-Ride Debrief</strong> on your phone while you're still at the barn. Not every section needs an answer‚Äîfollow what's meaningful for today's ride.</p>

            <div class="color-legend">
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #4A90E2;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Breakthrough:</strong> What worked</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #F5A623;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Aha Moment:</strong> What clicked</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #8B5CF6;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Connection:</strong> Your horse</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #7ED321;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Validation:</strong> Feedback</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #D0021B;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Challenge:</strong> What's hard</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #FF8C42;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Feel:</strong> Body awareness</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Weekly (10-15 Minutes)</h3>
            <p>Choose one <strong>Reflection</strong> from the six categories. These dig deeper into specific moments, challenges, or realizations. The prompts help trigger memories and guide your thinking. If a prompt doesn't resonate, pass it‚Äîyou get three passes per session.</p>

            <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>We'll send weekly reminders</strong> to complete a reflection, but don't wait for us! If something meaningful happens and you want to capture it immediately, go ahead. The reminders are there to help you maintain the habit, not restrict when you reflect.</p>

            <div class="emphasis">
                <strong>Unlock Your Dressage Journey Map:</strong> After completing 5 post-ride debriefs and 6 reflections (one from each category), you'll receive your personalized Journey Map. This interactive planning tool helps you set meaningful intentions for the year, identify your personal milestones and progress indicators, and create a framework for ongoing reflection. The more data you provide, the more personalized and insightful your Journey Map becomes.
            </div>

            <h3>The More You Collect, The More You Discover</h3>
            <p style="margin-top: 20px;">Think of data collection like building a puzzle. Five pieces show you a corner. Twenty pieces reveal a pattern. Fifty pieces show you the full picture. Be generous with your reflections and debriefs‚Äîeach one adds another data point that helps the AI identify what's really going on beneath the surface.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>The Six Reflection Categories</h2>
            
            <p style="margin-bottom: 20px;">Each week, pick one category that resonates with where you are right now. The goal is to capture one reflection from each category so your Journey Map has a complete picture of your riding experience.</p>

            <div class="color-legend" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr;">
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #4A90E2;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üü¶ Personal Milestone</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">Achievements, breakthroughs, goals met‚Äîthe wins that matter to you regardless of external recognition</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #7ED321;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üü© External Validation</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">Feedback from coaches, judges, peers‚Äîrecognition that moved you forward or shifted your perspective</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #F5A623;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üü® Aha Moment</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">The click, the realization, the sudden understanding‚Äîwhen theory connected to feeling or something finally made sense</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #D0021B;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üü• Obstacle</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">Challenges, setbacks, frustrations‚Äîthe hard parts of the journey including physical, mental, financial, or partnership issues</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #8B5CF6;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üü™ Connection</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">Moments with your horse‚Äîpartnership, communication, mutual understanding, trust building, and what they teach you</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #FF8C42;"></div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>üüß Feel (Body Awareness)</strong><br>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #666;">Physical sensations and discoveries‚Äîthe first time you felt your seat bones, recognized tension patterns, or understood biomechanics through your body</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° How Prompts Work</h4>
                <p>Each category has 25 prompts to trigger specific memories. When you select a category, you'll see one prompt. If it doesn't resonate, you can pass it (3 passes per session) to see another. The goal is to capture meaningful moments, not force responses to prompts that don't fit your experience.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Optional: Observation Form</h2>
            
            <p class="welcome-text">
                Beyond your own riding, there's tremendous value in capturing insights from <strong>watching others</strong>. The optional Observation Form lets you document learning moments when you:
            </p>

            <ul class="bullets">
                <li><strong>Attend a clinic</strong> as an auditor or participant</li>
                <li><strong>Watch your trainer ride your horse</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Observe training sessions</strong> at your barn</li>
                <li><strong>Audit a show</strong> or competition</li>
                <li><strong>Watch instructional videos</strong> or competitions online</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How It Works</h3>
            <p>The Observation Form is structured similarly to your reflections, allowing you to capture multiple learning moments from a single event using the relevant categories. Since you're observing rather than riding, the form uses five categories (Feel is not included as it captures your own body awareness while riding):</p>

            <div class="color-legend" style="margin: 20px 0;">
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #4A90E2;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Breakthrough:</strong> Technical or training breakthroughs you observed</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #F5A623;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Aha Moment:</strong> What resonated and how you could apply it</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #8B5CF6;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Connection:</strong> Horse-rider partnership dynamics</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #7ED321;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Validation:</strong> Concepts confirmed or validated</span>
                </div>
                <div class="color-item">
                    <div class="color-dot" style="background: #D0021B;"></div>
                    <span><strong>Obstacle:</strong> Challenges and how they were overcome</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Why This Matters</h3>
            <p>Observation data enriches your overall pattern analysis. When the AI sees both what you experience in the saddle AND what resonates when you watch others, it can identify gaps between what you recognize intellectually and what you're implementing practically. This reveals blind spots and accelerates learning transfer.</p>

            <div class="emphasis">
                <strong>Completely Optional:</strong> This form is available when opportunities arise‚Äîclinic auditing, watching lessons, video study sessions. There's no expectation or requirement to complete these during the pilot. But if you do have observation opportunities, capturing them adds another valuable dimension to your data.
            </div>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° Best Use Cases</h4>
                <p><strong>Most valuable:</strong> Watching your trainer ride your own horse (direct application to your partnership), attending clinics with instructors whose methods you want to understand better, or watching riders just one level above you (close enough to be immediately applicable).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Getting the Most Value</h2>
            
            <h3>Write for Future You, Not for Perfection</h3>
            <p>Three specific sentences beat one vague paragraph every time. "Slow to pick up right lead" is infinitely more useful than "horse was stiff." The AI finds patterns in specifics, not generalities.</p>

            <h3>Use Voice Input at the Barn</h3>
            <p>On mobile, tap the microphone icon in any text field. Talk through your observations while untacking‚Äîit's faster than typing and captures details you'd forget by the time you get home.</p>

            <h3>Set Intentions, Then Track Results</h3>
            <p>Before your ride, note what you're planning to focus on. After, note what actually happened. The gap between intention and result reveals where you need support.</p>

            <h3>Be Honest About the Hard Stuff</h3>
            <p>The AI learns most from obstacles and challenges. If you only record wins, the analysis won't have enough signal to help you break through plateaus.</p>

            <h3>Use "Compared To" Language</h3>
            <p>Adding comparison takes 5 seconds but multiplies value: "More balanced than last Tuesday" or "Stiffer than warmup" or "Better after the walk break." Context creates patterns.</p>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° The 2-Minute Rule</h4>
                <p>If completing a form feels like it's taking more than 5 minutes, you're overthinking it. Capture the key details and move on. Consistent 2-minute entries beat sporadic 20-minute essays.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Understanding Your Journey Map & AI Analysis</h2>
            
            <p style="margin-bottom: 20px;"><strong>Your first unlock is the Dressage Journey Map</strong>‚Äîan interactive planning and reflection tool built from your data. It helps you:</p>

            <ul class="bullets">
                <li>Define your big picture direction (2-5 year compass, not calendar)</li>
                <li>Set meaningful intentions for this year (qualities and direction, not just outcomes)</li>
                <li>Identify personal milestones that signal progress</li>
                <li>Think proactively about obstacles and course corrections</li>
                <li>Plan for ongoing check-ins and reflection</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="emphasis">
                <strong>From Data to Insights:</strong> Your Journey Map is populated with themes and patterns from your reflections and debriefs. The AI identifies what matters most to you, what conditions create success, where obstacles typically appear, and how you naturally course-correct. This becomes your personalized roadmap.
            </div>

            <p style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><strong>As you continue collecting data</strong>, you'll unlock additional AI coaching analysis in three distinct voices:</p>

            <div style="margin: 25px 0;">
                <div style="background: #FFF8F0; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #F5A623;">
                    <h4 style="color: #8B7355; margin-bottom: 10px;">üéØ The Stern Old World Master</h4>
                    <p>Direct, technically precise, high standards. No coddling, just clear assessment of what needs work. Choose this when you want unvarnished truth.</p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #F5F9FF; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #4A90E2;">
                    <h4 style="color: #8B7355; margin-bottom: 10px;">üìä The Neutral Analyst</h4>
                    <p>Data-focused, objective, evidence-based. Presents patterns without judgment. Choose this when you want clear facts without emotional coloring.</p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #F5FFF5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 4px solid #7ED321;">
                    <h4 style="color: #8B7355; margin-bottom: 10px;">üåü The Encouraging Instructor</h4>
                    <p>Supportive, progress-oriented, strengths-focused. Finds the growth in every challenge. Choose this when you need perspective and encouragement.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>All three coaches analyze the same data‚Äîthey just frame it differently. Use them based on what you need in the moment.</p>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° Data Volume Matters</h4>
                <p>The minimum to unlock your Journey Map is 5 debriefs + 6 reflections. But the real insights emerge at 15+ debriefs and 12+ reflections. The AI needs volume to distinguish between one-time events and meaningful patterns. Be generous with your data collection.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Important: Mobile Data Considerations</h2>
            
            <div class="warning-box">
                <h4>‚ö†Ô∏è Current Technical Limitation</h4>
                <p>The forms currently store data on your device using browser storage. This means:</p>
                <ul class="bullets" style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <li>Your data stays on the phone/device where you entered it</li>
                    <li>Clearing your browser data or cache will erase your entries</li>
                    <li>You'll need to copy/paste or email your entries to preserve them long-term</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>What we're doing about it:</strong> We're actively working on cloud storage and proper database solutions. Your feedback on data persistence is especially valuable.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <h4>üí° Protecting Your Data During the Pilot</h4>
                <ul class="bullets" style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <li>Use the export/copy functions after each entry</li>
                    <li>Email yourself the text periodically</li>
                    <li>Don't clear your browser data during the pilot period</li>
                    <li>Consider using the same device consistently</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

